ladders.explanation:
This building block involves using an ordered map (like TreeMap in Java or sorted dictionary) to store mappings from characters to their last occurrence indices. The key requirement is efficient retrieval of the minimum value (smallest last index) when we need to remove a character. An ordered map maintains keys in sorted order, but we need values sorted. We can either: 1) Use a map that supports O(1) min value retrieval (like maintaining separate sorted structure), or 2) Store entries sorted by value. The intuition is that we need to frequently find the character with the smallest last index when the window exceeds k distinct characters. With an unordered map, this would require O(k) linear scan each time. With proper ordered structure, we can achieve O(log k). Implementation approaches include: using TreeMap with custom comparator sorting by value, maintaining a min-heap alongside hash map, or using LinkedHashMap in access order. The algorithm involves: insert/update O(log k), delete O(log k), get-min O(1) or O(log k). Connection to L2: this data structure enables the core logic of finding minimum last occurrence efficiently. Common mistakes: using unordered map with linear search (O(k) instead of O(log k)), incorrect comparator implementation, or not handling updates properly. This building block is crucial for achieving O(n log k) overall time complexity.

Pseudocode:
class OrderedLastOccurrenceMap:
    def __init__(self):
        self.map = {}  # char -> last_index
        self.sorted_entries = SortedList()  # sorted by (last_index, char)

    def put(self, char, index):
        if char in self.map:
            old_index = self.map[char]
            self.sorted_entries.remove((old_index, char))
        self.map[char] = index
        self.sorted_entries.add((index, char))

    def delete(self, char):
        index = self.map[char]
        del self.map[char]
        self.sorted_entries.remove((index, char))

    def get_min_index(self):
        return self.sorted_entries[0][0] if self.sorted_entries else None

    def get_min_char(self):
        return self.sorted_entries[0][1] if self.sorted_entries else None

    def size(self):
        return len(self.map)

This is the most fundamental concept: counting how many distinct (different) characters are in a string. A distinct character is a unique character value, regardless of how many times it appears. For example, in "aabc", the distinct characters are 'a', 'b', 'c' - so count is 3, even though 'a' appears twice. The intuition is simple: we need to identify all unique characters. The basic algorithm: create an empty set, iterate through each character in the string, add each character to the set (sets automatically handle duplicates), then return the size of the set. Time complexity is O(n) where n is string length, as we process each character once. Space complexity is O(k) where k is number of distinct characters (at most min(n, alphabet size)). This foundation connects to L4 because we need to track distinct characters to enforce the "at most k distinct" constraint. Common mistakes: confusing distinct characters with total characters, or not handling empty strings. Understanding this concept is essential before tackling the sliding window problem.

Pseudocode:
function countDistinctChars(s):
    if s is empty:
        return 0

    distinct_set = empty set

    for each character c in s:
        add c to distinct_set

    return size of distinct_set

